A.B. 209
ASSEMBLY BILL NO. 209–ASSEMBLYMEMBER ORENTLICHER
PREFILED FEBRUARY 3, 2025
____________
Referred to Committee on Judiciary
SUMMARY—Provides immunity from criminal liability for
engaging in prostitution or committing certain acts
while engaged in prostitution. (BDR 15-781)
FISCAL NOTE: Effect on Local Government: No.
Effect on the State: No.
~
EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to crimes; providing immunity from criminal
liability for engaging in prostitution or committing certain
acts while engaged in prostitution under certain
circumstances; and providing other matters properly
relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law requires a peace officer who detains, arrests or issues a citation to
2 a prostitute for a violation of the prohibition against unlawfully engaging in
3 prostitution or solicitation for prostitution to provide information relating to certain
4 assistance for which the prostitute might be eligible. Existing law also requires a
5 prosecuting attorney to dismiss the charge against a prostitute for such a violation if
6 the prosecuting attorney has reason to believe that the prostitute is a victim of sex
7 trafficking. (NRS 201.353)
8 Section 2 of this bill declares that it is the public policy of this State to
9 encourage the ability of victims and witnesses of serious violent crimes to report
10 and participate in the criminal justice system without fear of criminal prosecution
11 for engaging in prostitution or committing certain acts while engaged in
12 prostitution. Section 3 of this bill provides that a person who violates certain
13 provisions of existing law relating to prostitution, controlled substances or certain
14 acts relating to vagrancy is immune from criminal liability if, during the course of
15 allegedly engaging in prostitution, the person: (1) is a victim or witness to certain
16 serious violent offenses; and (2) seeks certain assistance. Section 4 of this bill
17 applies the definitions in existing law relating to prostitution to sections 2 and 3.
